// ---------------------------------------------------------------- introduction
#slide(title: [Introduction and Motivations])[
  #emph[La Ghigliottina] (final round of #emph[L'Eredità]): five clue words, find the one word
  that connects to all five.

  #v(4pt)
  The link is *not* semantic similarity, it is *collocational and cultural*: the answer forms
  a fixed multi-word expression, compound, or idiom with each clue.

  #v(8pt)
  #align(center)[
    #box(inset: 10pt, fill: luma(240), radius: 6pt)[
      `legno · forte · continua · malattia · veloce` #h(6pt) $=>$ #h(6pt) `cassa`
    ]
  ]
  #v(4pt)
  #align(center)[
    #text(size: 16pt)[cassa di legno · cassaforte · cassa continua · cassa malattia · cassa]
  ]

  #v(8pt)
  #emph[Distributional models (word2vec/fastText) are a poor structural fit -- the signal is
  syntagmatic, not paradigmatic.]
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- related work
#slide(title: [Related Work (1)])[
  The EVALITA NLP4FUN shared task framed #emph[La Ghigliottina] as a computational language
  game. The seminal player _OTTHO_ (Basile et al. 2009) solved it by _knowledge infusion_,
  retrieval / co-occurrence over a dictionary, proverb lists, and Wikipedia, and *beat
  learned-embedding methods*, the outcome we reproduce.

  #v(10pt)
  The best system, _Il Mago della Ghigliottina_ / _UNIOR4NLP_ (Sangati et al. 2018, 2020),
  same MWE hypothesis, same resources (PAISÀ, De Mauro #emph[polirematiche], proverbs,
  compounds), reaches *61.0%* (2018) / *68.6%* (2020). This project set out to replicate and
  extend it, but fell short: our reproduction hits only *0.31*, and no extension moved acc\@1.
]

#slide(title: [Related Work (2)])[
  Our contribution is not a new model but a controlled ablation showing why the shortfall is
  a coverage gap, not a scoring one:
  #v(4pt)
  - Their edge is broader curated resources (itWaC, Wikipedia titles, larger MWE/proverb lists).
  - On ~30k entities, knowledge-graph embeddings are dominated by *hubness*.
  - Every recall-broadening extension trades top-1 accuracy for rank-tail recall.
  - The signal is *syntagmatic*, so word2vec / fastText are a poor structural fit.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- approach
#slide(title: [Proposed Approach])[
  + *Typed, weighted word graph* from PAISÀ. Edge #emph[types] are MWE-bearing patterns --
    `MOD` (noun–adj), `BINOMIAL` (X e Y), `DI` (X di Y), `DA` (X da Y). Edge #emph[weights]
    are *pattern-conditioned PPMI* (PMI within each relation's own pairs).
  + *Curated `IDIOM` edges* from Italian #emph[polirematiche] + proverbs (≈18.5k pairs).
    They supply the clue$->$answer links running text can't -- added at a constant weight.
  + *Flat PPMI-sum solver*. Per clue take the strongest edge to a candidate (max over
    relations/directions), then sum across the five clues. Highest sum wins.
  + _Optional_ *description pass*. A local Qwen3-1.7B explains the answer, one sentence
    per clue, post-hoc, plays no part in solving.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- main result
#slide(title: [Main result])[
  Full PAISÀ graph (600k triples / 32k entities), EVALITA 2018 test (100 games).

  #v(10pt)
  #align(center)[
    #rtable(
      columns: 7,
      align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center),
      inset: (x: 10pt, y: 6pt),
      table.hline(),
      table.header[Configuration][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@5][acc\@10][acc\@100],
      table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
      [flat-PPMI(sum), PAISÀ only], [60], [0.288], [0.240], [0.330], [0.380], [0.600],
      [*+ IDIOM (w=5.5)*], [*67*], [*0.384*], [*0.310*], [*0.480*], [*0.520*], [*0.670*],
      [IDIOM alone (no corpus)], [43], [0.206], [0.160], [0.240], [0.270], [0.430],
      table.hline(),
    )
  ]

  #v(8pt)
  Curated idiom edges are the *single largest lever* in the project: acc\@1 0.24 $->$ *0.31*
  (+29% rel), MRR 0.29 $->$ 0.38.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- idiom weight tuning
#slide(title: [Tuning the idiom weight (1)])[
  The idiom edge weight is the one free scalar tuned on the *train* split (965 games,
  `tools/idiom_tune.py`), then held fixed on test. By plotting the idiom edge weight
  against acc\@1, we get an inverted-U, with a peak *$"acc@1" = 0.263$ at $w = 5.5$*.
]

#slide(title: [Tuning the idiom weight (2)])[
  #align(center + horizon)[
    #let ws = (0.0,0.5,1.0,1.5,2.0,2.5,3.0,3.5,4.0,4.5,5.0,5.5,6.0,6.5,7.0,7.5,8.0,8.5,9.0,9.5,10.0)
    #let accs = (0.1668,0.1699,0.1741,0.1824,0.1938,0.2021,0.2145,0.2218,0.2352,0.2456,0.2580,0.2632,0.2601,0.2591,0.2580,0.2477,0.2404,0.2311,0.2290,0.2259,0.2259)
    #lq.diagram(
      width: 20cm, height: 7.5cm,
      xlabel: [`IDIOM` edge weight],
      ylabel: [train acc\@1],
      lq.plot(ws, accs, mark: "o", mark-size: 3.5pt, stroke: accent),
      lq.plot((5.5,), (0.2632,), mark: "o", mark-size: 7pt, stroke: none, color: red),
    )
  ]
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- description quality
#slide(title: [Description quality])[
  The optional `--describe` explanations (Qwen3-1.7B) scored vs. the gold `desc` field
  (100 test games), generated for the solver's own top-1 prediction:

  #v(8pt)
  #align(center)[
    #rtable(
      columns: 6,
      align: (center, center, center, center, center, center),
      inset: (x: 10pt, y: 6pt),
      table.hline(),
      table.header[BLEU][ROUGE-1][ROUGE-2][ROUGE-L][ROUGE-Lsum][BERTScore],
      table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
      [1.70], [0.248], [0.035], [0.177], [0.170], [*0.658*],
      table.hline(),
    )
  ]
  #v(4pt)
  #align(center)[#text(size: 15pt)[BLEU on the sacreBLEU 0–100 scale; the rest 0–1.]]

  #v(8pt)
  The BLEU, ROUGE-1, ROUG-E-2, and ROUGE-L scores are low, showing a low $n$-gram overlap.
  This is to be expected, as the generated text is free-form Italian, but the BERTScore
  shows the explanations are semantically on-topic.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- what didn't work
#slide(title: [Explored Extensions and Negative Results])[
  Every extension improves recall / MRR / acc\@{10,100}, but *none improves acc\@1.*

  #v(8pt)
  #grid(columns: (1fr, 1fr), gutter: 18pt,
    [
      *Models / scorers*
      - KGE (ComplEx, RotatE) -- acc\@1 0.04 (hubness)
      - Personalised PageRank -- acc\@1 0.05
      - Coverage / logsum scorers
      - Learned re-ranker (10 features)
    ],
    [
      *More data / more edges*
      - Wikipedia, itWaC joins (register miss)
      - OpenSubtitles (helps recall, not top-1)
      - COMPOUND, SIM (fastText) edges
      - Wiktionary MWEs, ConceptNet
    ],
  )

  #v(10pt)
  #align(center)[
    #box(inset: 10pt, fill: luma(240), radius: 6pt)[
      ~8 independent experiments · all confirm the same ceiling
    ]
  ]
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- KGE
#slide(title: [Knowledge-graph embeddings -- decisive loss])[
  The project's original thesis: learned embeddings could score #emph[unobserved]
  clue$->$answer links a graph baseline can't.

  #v(8pt)
  #align(center)[
    #rtable(
      columns: 4,
      align: (left, center, center, center),
      inset: (x: 12pt, y: 6pt),
      table.hline(),
      table.header[Method][found][MRR][acc\@1],
      table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
      [*flat-PPMI(sum)*], [*60*], [*0.288*], [*0.240*],
      [KGE ComplEx (300 ep)], [21], [0.023], [0.010],
      [KGE RotatE (150 ep)], [37], [0.068], [0.040],
      table.hline(),
    )
  ]

  #v(8pt)
  Over ~30k entities, link prediction is dominated by *hubness* -- frequent adjectives /
  prepositions absorb probability mass, so the model smears its score instead of pinning the
  collocate (known partners rank #box[\#66–170]).
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- register
#slide(title: [Additional corpora -- register beats volume])[
  Extra corpora joined into the PPMI scan (PAISÀ-defined candidates):

  #v(8pt)
  #align(center)[
    #rtable(
      columns: 5,
      align: (left, center, center, center, left),
      inset: (x: 12pt, y: 6pt),
      table.hline(),
      table.header[Added corpus][+tokens][acc\@1][acc\@100][verdict],
      table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
      [-- (PAISÀ only)], [--], [0.240], [0.600], [baseline],
      [Wikipedia], [+650M], [0.240], [0.610], [recall only],
      [*OpenSubtitles 12M*], [+85M], [*0.270*], [0.630], [*helps*],
      [OpenSubtitles full], [+766M], [0.250], [0.660], [recall ↑, top-1 ↓],
      [itWaC (web)], [+93M], [0.220], [0.600], [hurts],
      table.hline(),
    )
  ]

  #v(8pt)
  Dialogue (85M tokens) beats Wikipedia (which doubled the graph). But nothing beats the
  curated idiom edges, the purest register match.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- ceiling
#slide(title: [The recall-miss anatomy -- why the ceiling exists])[
  Gold-rank anatomy of the 100 test games:

  #v(6pt)
  #align(center)[
    #rtable(
      columns: 4,
      align: (center, center, center, center),
      inset: (x: 16pt, y: 6pt),
      table.hline(),
      table.header[rank \#1][rank 2–10][rank 11–100][missing (>100)],
      table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
      [31], [21], [17], [*31*],
      table.hline(),
    )
  ]

  #v(10pt)
  - The 31 misses *exist as graph nodes* but lack the clue$->$answer *edges* (98/100 gold already
    in vocab -- coverage is not the problem).
  - Training a re-ranker on the 965 train games does not help, it gave only 2 games difference on top-1.
  - SIM / ConceptNet left train `found` essentially unchanged, it was the wrong kind of edge, not the missing syntagmatic collocations.
]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------- conclusion
#slide(title: [Conclusions and Limitations])[
  A minimal system, typed pattern-PPMI over PAISÀ + curated idiom edges + flat sum,
  reaches *acc\@1 0.31 / MRR 0.38* on EVALITA 2018 NLP4FUN, beating KGE, PageRank, and every
  corpus/edge extension.

  #v(8pt)
  *The lesson:* the task is bottlenecked by register-matched recall, not model
  sophistication. The one lever that ever moved top-1 was the idiom register.

  #v(8pt)
  *Next step:* a register-matched, associative phrase resource.
]

